04821nam a22006615i 9780271073286DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20211991pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710732867 a10.1515/97802710732862doi  a(DE-B1597)583742  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aD568.4.L45bA64 1991eb 7aHIS0370102bisacsh04a940.4150922221 aAllen, Malcolm D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Medievalism of Lawrence of Arabia /cMalcolm D. Allen. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©1991  a1 online resource (236 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAbbreviations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Origins of a Medievalist -- t2. The Nonliterary Background to Lawrence's Medievalism -- t3. Lawrence and the Medieval Revival -- t4. Lawrence's Early Medieval Reading -- t5. The Impact of W. S. Blunt -- t6. Chivalry and the Nomadic Code -- t7. Lawrence's Literary Medievalism -- t8. Seuen Pillars and Neomedieval Romance -- t9. Lawrence and Ruskinian Medievalism -- t10. Further Questionings of the Chivalric Ethos -- t11. Lawrence the Ascetic -- tConclusion -- tAppendix: "Orientalism" and the Undiscovered Subtexts in Seven Pillars of Whdom -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aM. D. Allen's study deals with T. E. Lawrence's lifelong interest in the medieval world, especially medieval literature, and its considerable influence on his view of himself and of the Arabs with whom he fought in an archaic theater of war, and hence his own literary production. The Medievalism of Lawrence of Arabia investigates the influence Lawrence's interest in medieval life and literature had on his attitudes toward life in general and-in content, theme, and diction-on his masterpiece, Seven Pillars of Wisdom, in particular. Allen begins with a brief biography of Lawrence-his early interest in things medieval and his somewhat controversial BA thesis on crusader castles. Allen then reveals the extent to which Lawrence's ideas about honor, warfare, and chivalry in the Arab war against the Turks were shaped by his reading in medieval writings such as Malory's Morte d'Arthur. (Both, as he makes clear, were warrior societies dominated by horses.) Lawrence's reading in the nineteenth-century medievalism is also explored, as in Tennyson's Idylls of the King, and Ruskin's writing on art, where the parallel between Ruskin's ideas on ornament and Lawrence's ideas about the dignity of war is demonstrated. Allen then identifies the medieval and neomedieval texts of Seven Pillars of Wisdom and shows why and to what effect Lawrence borrowed from chivalric, neochivalric, and pseudochivalric works, and sometimes transmogrified them, revealing Lawrence's greatest inspiration to be an English translation of the Moallakat (which is, so to speak, the Arabic Beowulf). Allen sheds new light on many aspects of the influence of medievalism on Lawrence's thought and writing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aMedievalismzEnglandxHistoryy20th century. 0aMedievalismzMiddle EastxHistoryy20th century. 0aSoldiers' writings, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271073286zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271073286423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271073286.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_E